                Y<lb/></p>
            <p>Hon. Joseph Blumenthal<lb/>
                My Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I regret my not having met you at various times when<lb/> I called at your office.<lb/></p>
            <p>I desired to have our interview on different topics.<lb/>  What I now say&#44; however&#44; requires your attention in connection <sic>w ith</sic><lb/> that of your colleagues.<lb/></p>
            <p>The two lads who have been studying with me are poor.<lb/>  From time to time I have given them some help.  Finding that the plan<lb/> of collecting from private individuals does not answer&#44; I arrived<lb/> at the conclusion that I ought to ask the assistance of the J. T. S.<lb/></p>
            <p>The boys&#39; parents could not remove to N. Y. and were<lb/> they willing to part with the children&#44; the latter would cost<lb/> the institution much more than I have occasionally afforded them.<lb/></p>
            <p>I talked the matter over with Dr. S. S. Cohen&#44; and he<lb/> coincided with me&#44; that a requisition from the general funds would<lb/> be within the line of our working.<lb/></p>
            <p>So far the two students have received about a dollar<lb/> a week each.  Will you have the kindness to consult the Board of<lb/> Trustees&#44; and let me hear at your convenience&#63;  Our Branch&#44; I<lb/> think&#44; has done well.  I shall be in Baltimore next Sunday and I<lb/> will try to improve the occasion by putting in a good word on<lb/> behalf of the sacred cause.<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours truly&#44;<lb/> S. MORAIS<lb/></p>
            <p>Nov. 23rd&#44; 1891<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
